BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:5-vcjYUSSA0Thrz5HzM-D
SUMMARY:Chuckle Bucket Tuesday @ Club Comedy Seattle (Open Mic)
DTSTAMP:20260401T044552Z
DTSTART:20260408T020000Z
DESCRIPTION:Club Comedy Seattle hosts Chuckle Bucket Tuesday each week. The
	 luck of the bucket rules the night. Comics drop their name in and hope to
	 be drawn for one of the spots on the list to tell jokes. It's fun\, fast-
	paced and will keep you laughing hard on your Tuesday night.\n\nDoor 7:00P
	M/Show 7:30PM\n\nAdmission: $7 \\+ $0.35 City Of Seattle Admission Tax\n\n
	21\\+ With Valid ID REQUIRED for entry. NO REFUNDS.\n\nFYI: If you have a 
	large party it's easier for us to seat you all together if you purchase al
	l the tickets under one name.\n\n.\n\nClub Comedy Seattle FAQ\n\nIs there 
	an age/ID requirement?\n\nYes. We are strictly 21\\+ and valid physical ID
	 is REQUIRED For Entry\n\nIs Seating First Come/First Served?\n\nYes. The 
	room is all two top tables and we seat guests in the order in which they a
	rrive.\n\nCan I reserve a table for a group?\n\nWe do not take reservation
	s for tables\, but groups can arrive early to secure seating together.\n\n
	Are tickets available at the door if an event is sold out online?\n\nIf an
	 event is sold out online there are no tickets available at the door.\n\nW
	hat are the club’s hours of operation?\n\nThe club is open Tuesday to Sund
	ay. Doors open a half hour before each show.\n\nWhat is the Parking like?\
	n\nGenerally there is street parking available in the blocks surrounding t
	he club. There are also affordable parking lots on 16th Ave E right around
	 the block from the club along with other easy options in the neighborhood
	\n\nIs there a dress code?\n\nThere is no formal dress code\, but we recom
	mend smart casual attire.\n\nCan I bring food or drinks?\n\nOutside food a
	nd drinks are not allowed. We have a full bar and a menu available for you
	r enjoyment.\n\nWhat if I can't make it and need to cancel my ticket?\n\nA
	ll ticket sales are final. However\, if you can’t make it\, please contact
	 us through Eventbrite in advance\, and we’ll do our best to accommodate y
	ou.\n\nWill there be an opener for the headliner?\n\nYes\, headliner shows
	 feature a lineup of comedians\, including a host\, an opener\, and the he
	adliner.\n\nWill the comics talk to me like I see in online videos all the
	 time?\n\nMost likely they won't. Crowd work videos are popular for postin
	g online\, but crowd work doesn't generally happen at the online frequency
	 in live comedy show situations. Some comics do engage the crowd as part o
	f their regular set and it's generally always fun and more about making fu
	n of themselves than making fun of the crowd.\n\nHow can I get on the Chea
	p Laughs Open Mic On Wednesdays?\n\nSubmissions for spots on the Wednesday
	 Cheap Laughs Open Mic are accepted only on the Tuesday before between 12:
	00AM and 11:59PM via email at openmic@clubcomedyseattle.com\n\nDo you offe
	r group discounts?\n\nYes\, we offer discounts for groups of ten or more. 
	Please contact us for more details.\n\nCan I meet the comedians after the 
	show?\n\nMeet-and-greet opportunities vary by event. Please ask staff for 
	details after the show.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/c
	huckle-bucket-tuesday-club-comedy-seattle-open-mic/18474121/2026-04-07T00\
	n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/chuckle-bucket-tuesday-cl
	ub-comedy-seattle-open-mic/18474121/2026-04-07T00
LOCATION:Club Comedy Seattle\, 328 15th Ave E\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H30M
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:XwWfypd4Q1zgWMkJQm0rA
SUMMARY:Beyond Mysticism: The Modern Northwest
DTSTAMP:20260401T044552Z
DTSTART:20260408T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:image: Drift No. 2\, 1936\, Malcolm M. Roberts\, American\, 191
	3-1990\, tempera on board\, 25 1/2 x 20 5/8 in.\, Seattle Art Museum\, Eug
	ene Fuller Memorial Collection\, 37.103\, © Malcolm M. Roberts\, photo: Sc
	ott Leen.\n\nInspired by the region’s natural beauty and rapidly changing 
	city\, this exhibition showcases artists who told the raw story of Seattle
	 in the 20th century. By sharing the Pacific Northwest’s perspective throu
	gh trending art styles—including Social Realism\, Surrealism\, and Abstrac
	t Expressionism—these artists offered a unique take on Modernist art and c
	hallenged the “mystic” label ascribed to their works.\n\nSpearheading the 
	movement were local icons Mark Tobey\, Kenneth Callahan\, Guy Anderson\, a
	nd Morris Graves—but the range and breadth of Pacific Northwest art goes b
	eyond the “Big Four” of the Northwest School. Featuring more than 150 piec
	es\, this exhibition showcases works that investigate the complexities of 
	daily life in the region. Whether applying an ecocritical lens or producin
	g dreamy and uncanny visuals\, these artists expressed the duality of the 
	natural world and city life to warn of the environmental and social impact
	s of industrialization.\n\nFrom Malcolm Roberts to Kenjiro Nomura\, learn 
	how Northwest artists applied their regional perspective to broader artist
	ic developments to create a new form of American Modernism.\n\nThe exhibit
	ion is accompanied by a fully illustrated catalogue authored by Theresa Pa
	panikolas\, SAM’s Ann M. Barwick Curator of American Art.\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-modern-northwest/183
	08126/2026-04-08T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-mode
	rn-northwest/18308126/2026-04-08T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:z1OAIzPDHPWMyIOATGkL3
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260401T044552Z
DTSTART:20260408T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-08T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-08T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:md_RuFffiZCfnFcedL19q
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260401T044552Z
DTSTART:20260408T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	4-08T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-04-08T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:n4sqCqCa9UmufZ9zwAQf-
SUMMARY:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light
DTSTAMP:20260401T044552Z
DTSTART:20260408T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light invites you to become par
	t of the art. Agha\, a Pakistani American artist\, animates spaces with he
	r large-scale sculptural installations. Suspended from the ceiling\, Agha’
	s steel cubes are laser-cut with intricate designs that project geometric 
	shadows onto the visitor. She draws on both the light and dark of her own 
	life\, using South Asian art practices to convey the gender discrimination
	 she faced growing up as a young girl in Pakistan. An in-depth exploration
	 of Islamic architecture\, art\, and identity\, this is the first solo exh
	ibition of a Pakistani American artist in SAM’s 90-year history. Agha is c
	arving a name out for herself in the art world—visit the Seattle Asian Art
	 Museum for an immersive and illuminating experience.\n\nhttps://seatoday.
	6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geometry-of-light/16795597
	/2026-04-08T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geomet
	ry-of-light/16795597/2026-04-08T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:X6bB_N0VJv0GYqwUN9F2a
SUMMARY:Boren Banner Series: Camille Trautman
DTSTAMP:20260401T044552Z
DTSTART:20260408T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Every photograph is a reminder that the act of framing is never
	 neutral. In Camille Trautman’s first solo museum exhibition in their home
	town\, the Seattle-born Duwamish artist uses photography and video to chal
	lenge colonial narratives and counter Indigenous erasure. The exhibition p
	resents selections from their ongoing series The North American LCD—spectr
	al self-portraits staged in varied natural landscapes. Rooted in Trautman’
	s process of coming out as transgender\, the images show the artist’s body
	 partially obscured by large LCD screens. The series examines how both lan
	dscape photography and digital media can shape or distort cultural identit
	y\, often by promoting or denying visibility.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.
	com/events/#/details/boren-banner-series-camille-trautman/16813305/2026-04
	-08T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/boren-banner-series-camil
	le-trautman/16813305/2026-04-08T00
LOCATION:Frye Art Museum\, 704 Terry Ave\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT6H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:JD9_uoSGyzmv9PVjs1y6_
SUMMARY:Mary Jane
DTSTAMP:20260401T044552Z
DTSTART:20260408T210000Z
DESCRIPTION:Mary Jane is a cheerful caregiver and unflagging advocate for h
	er toddler\, Alex\, who lives with cerebral palsy and chronic illness—but 
	the American healthcare system can wear anybody down\, especially a single
	 parent. While navigating her son’s health challenges\, Mary Jane meets an
	d builds community with women from all walks of life\, experiencing joy an
	d connection amidst the distress and heartbreak. Poignantly humorous and d
	eeply cathartic\, this semi-autobiographical drama by Tony-nominated playw
	right Amy Herzog is a love letter to caregivers and support systems of all
	 kinds.\n\nBy Amy Herzog\n\nDirected by Allison Narver\n\nhttps://seatoday
	.6amcity.com/events/#/details/mary-jane/17504962/2026-04-08T00\n\nFrom SEA
	today - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/mary-jane/17504962/2026-0
	4-08T00
LOCATION:Leo K. Theater\, 155 Mercer St.\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:PHjwvmZnCN1l3pUd2hbjR
SUMMARY:SP 101: Intro to Vera's Screen Print Studio
DTSTAMP:20260401T044552Z
DTSTART:20260409T010000Z
DESCRIPTION:This 2-hour\, comprehensive hands-on class teaches you all the 
	basics of screen printing at VERA’s screen printing studio: From hand-draw
	ing a stencil on transparency\, coating and burning a screen\, to pulling 
	your very first print! Get comfortable with Vera's shop layout\, equipment
	\, and culture. Learn techniques for creating screens\, terminology\, and 
	more to create 1-color projects in the print shop. Students will walk away
	 with the basic skills for screen printing 1-color paper prints\, and thei
	r own print of a special Vera design\, specific to the 101 class. This cla
	ss is a prerequisite for 200-level classes at VERA\, as well as access to 
	Open Sessions to work on your own projects in VERA’s screen printing studi
	o.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/sp-101-intro-to-vera-s
	-screen-print-studio/14809998/2026-04-08T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Cult
	ure
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/sp-101-intro-to-vera-s-sc
	reen-print-studio/14809998/2026-04-08T00
LOCATION:Book-It Repertory Theatre\, 305 Harrison Street\, Seattle\, WA
